  "prompt": "What is the speed of light in a vacuum dependent on?",
  "response": "The speed of light in a vacuum is a fundamental constant of nature and is independent of the motion of the source or the observer. It is **not dependent** on any physical or environmental factors, such as:\n\n1. **The motion of the source**: Whether the light source is moving toward or away from the observer does not change the speed of light.\n2. **The frequency or wavelength of light**: All electromagnetic waves, regardless of their frequency or wavelength, travel at the same speed in a vacuum.\n3. **The medium**: In a vacuum, there is no medium to affect the speed of light (unlike in materials like air, water, or glass, where light slows down).\n\nThe speed of light in a vacuum (\\( c \\)) is determined by the properties of the electromagnetic field and is given by:\n\n\\[\nc = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mu_0 \\epsilon_0}}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( \\mu_0 \\) is the permeability of free space.\n- \\( \\epsilon_0 \\) is the permittivity of free space.\n\nThese values are constants, making \\( c \\) a universal constant. Its exact value is \\( 299,792,458 \\) meters per second (m/s).",
